title: Shooting Targets (Phoenix Police Department)

communications.subject: Arizona Public Records Law Request: Shooting Targets (Phoenix Police Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Arizona Public Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

I am requesting records related to the purchase and use of targets used for marksmanship training:

Targets are defined as paper and metal targets used by the department for shooting lethal and nonlethal weapons (40mm foam rounds, tasers, etc). They can be stationary or moving. 

Purchase and invoice records for targets
Scans, photos, website links, and any record that shows what the targets look like

Search 2018 to today’s date.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Joey Scott

title: CPRA Request – Michael Crowe Case Records (January 1998)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: CPRA Request – Michael Crowe Case Records (January 1998)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I am formally requesting access to all available public records relating to the investigation, prosecution, and subsequent dismissal of charges in the case of Michael Crowe, who was interrogated in January 1998 by the Escondido Police Department in connection with the murder of Stephanie Crowe.

 Requested Records:

1. Case files, charging documents, and dismissal filings related to Michael Crowe and co-defendants in the Stephanie Crowe homicide case.


2. Memos, legal briefs, and notes from the suppression hearing where the confession was deemed coerced.


3. Expert witness reports or psychological assessments of the interrogation techniques used.


4. Correspondence and internal discussions between the DA's Office and Escondido Police Department concerning:

The admissibility of the confession

The decision to file or drop charges

Public/media inquiries


5. Training or policy memos reflecting lessons learned from the Michael Crowe case, if available.


6. Any statements or interviews prepared by the DA's Office regarding the exoneration and later developments in the case.

 Request Details:

Subject: Michael Crowe, then age 14

Incident: Interrogated Jan. 21–23, 1998, for the murder of Stephanie Crowe

Outcome: Conviction thrown out; found factually innocent by a judge in 2012

Jurisdiction: San Diego County, California

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brown Pearl

Sincerely,

communications.subject: RE: FOIL Request - New Submission
communications.communication:
Dear Akash Mehta:



Your Freedom of Information Law ("FOIL") request, dated April 15, 2025, sought the following records from the Office of the New York City Comptroller:



"Pursuant to the New York Freedom of Information Law, I hereby request the following records:

The full text of the following contracts:

CT107120238805437
CT107120238804237
CT107120248807555
CT107120228807358
CT107120238804456
CT107120121416261
CT107120228803428
CT107120228803527
CT107120248807653"



Your request is granted. Copies of the requested contracts are available to download using the secure ShareFile link: https://nyccomptroller.sharefile.com/i/ife70aff683c45c49. The link expires in 30 days.



New York Public Officers Law ("POL") § 87(2)(a) permits an agency to deny access to portions of records that are "specifically exempted from disclosure by state or federal statute." Specifically, under Social Services Law § 136(1), which makes confidential "the names and addresses of persons applying for or receiving public assistance and care" (emphasis added), the names and addresses identifying the location of shelter sites have been redacted from the records.



Furthermore, under N.Y.S. Public Officers Law ("POL") §§ 87(2)(b) and 89(2)(b), the resumes of non-governmental employees have been redacted to prevent an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy. See also N.Y.S. POL §§ 89(2)(b)(i) and 89(2)(b)(iv), which states that an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy includes, but shall not be limited to, "disclosure of employment, medical or credit histories or personal references of applicants for employment . . . and disclosure of information of a personal nature when disclosure would result in economic or personal hardship to the subject party and such information is not relevant to the work of the agency requesting or maintaining it."



Under N.Y.S. Public Officers Law § 89(4), you have the right to appeal. Appeals must be submitted within 30 calendar days of receipt of this response and should be submitted by email to FOIL@comptroller.nyc.gov<mailto:FOIL@comptroller.nyc.gov>. Please put "FOIL Appeal" in the email's subject field. Appeals may also be mailed to the following address:



FOIL Appeals Officer

New York City Comptroller's Office

Office of the General Counsel

One Centre Street, Suite 602

New York, NY 10007



If you have any questions regarding your request, please send an email to our FOIL Officer at foil@comptroller.nyc.gov<mailto:foil@comptroller.nyc.gov>.



Sincerely,

NYC Comptroller's Office FOIL Unit

communications.subject: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1. All email correspondence, with attachments, mentioning "Water Property Investors," "Water Property Investor II," or "Water Property Investor III." 

2. Pitch decks, prospectuses, or any other materials provided to NMERB by the the above funds for consideration of potential investments.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 15 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Julia Rock

Dear Records Requestor:


Your request for information from the New Mexico Educational Retirement Board was forwarded to me. In accordance with the New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act (IPRA), “a written request shall provide the name, address and telephone number of the person seeking access to the records and shall identify the records sought with reasonable particularity.” Section 14-2-8(C) NMSA 1978.


If you will provide me with your name and mailing address, we can begin the process of allowing inspection of the relevant records.


The Inspection of Public Records Act can be found at 14-2-1 through 14-2-12 NMSA 1978.


Thank you.


Amanda Olsen

communications.subject: RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock,

I am responding to your email yesterday requesting any additional info regarding the source of delays on this request. Please be assured that we make every effort to respond promptly to every request. However, we must also ensure that we are diligent and accurate in our reply. Thus, when obtained, all documents and emails must be reviewed. Additionally, we must rely on the state agency that controls the entire state email system to identify and provide the emails requested. As you can imagine, the process takes time.

As to an estimated response date, in our letter of August 1, 2023, we noted that we intend to respond by September 6, 2023.

Thank you for your patience and please feel free to contact me if you have further questions.

Respectfully,

communications.subject: ATTORNEY CLIENT PRIVILEGED - RE: [EXTERNAL] RE: New Mexico Inspection of Public Records Act Request: Water Asset Management funds correspondence
communications.communication:
Dear Ms. Rock and Ms. Burns,

Thank you for your inquiry and please accept our apologies for the delay.

As Mr. Scroggins noted in his August 3, 2023 email regarding our projected response, we always try to be prompt.  But as you might guess, the request references a large number of records.  As he said, we must thoroughly review all records to identify and obtain the responsive documents from both external and internal sources.  It is a complex and time-consuming process.

I am confident that we will have documents ready to provide on or before the December 6th, 2023, date noted in our recent communication.

Thank you for your continued patience!
Regards,
Renee

title: simplified acquisitions and micro purchasing POC's

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: simplified acquisitions and micro purchasing POC's
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I request a list of all points of contact or contracting officers and their contact info for both simplified acquisitions and micro purchasing at FTC covering the entire Agency. If too broad, a list of all those with procurement or purchasing authority will suffice.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

David Joyce

communications.subject: Thank you
communications.communication:
Hello,

Thank you for submitting your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to the Federal Trade Commission (FTC). Someone from our office will reach out to you as soon as possible regarding the status of your request.

Sincerely,

The FTC FOIA Unit

title: Cosmetology programs

communications.subject: Tennessee Public Records Act Request: Cosmetology programs
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Tennessee Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) Pass rates on the state cosmetology licensing exam, broken down by school, between 1/1/2023 to the present

2) Copies of all complaints, from 1/1/2022 through present, regarding the following institutions, inclusive of any and all their campuses:

Tennessee School of Beauty of Knoxville Inc
Paul Mitchell the School
Empire Beauty School
Gould's Academy
TC Beauty
Austin's Beauty College Inc
Genesis Career College-Lebanon
The Hair Academy LLC
Franklin Hair Academy School of Cosmetology
Sandra Academy of Salon Services


If the complaints are too numerous by page and would require a cost estimate, please send me a spreadsheet of the complaints, which includes the complaint information, without the attachments.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 7 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Meredith Kolodner

title: SOR and Community Supervision

communications.subject: Maine Freedom of Access Act Request: SOR and Community Supervision
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maine Freedom of Access Act, I hereby request the following records:

The exact number of people who are 

1) on both the sex offender registry and probation; and
2) on both the sex offender registry and parole;

as per the latest available data is requested.

communications.subject: **FOAA Request** 202572 Wendy Sawyer 21 Jul 25
communications.communication:
The Maine Department of Corrections has received your request for information under the Maine Freedom of Access Act (FOAA).  Your request will be evaluated to determine if it comes within the FOAA, if it is clear as to what information you are requesting, and if nonconfidential records already exist that would fulfill all or part of your request.  If your request does not come within the FOAA, is not clear, or no records exist, you will be so notified.  If records exist, but they are confidential, you will be notified of the basis for that determination.  If nonconfidential records exist, you will be provided a good faith, nonbinding estimate of the time within which you will be provided the records, as well as an estimate of the costs that are allowed by the FOAA, if applicable.

V/r

Jenna Heald

title: Request on Political Appointees (Environmental Protection Agency)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request on Political Appointees (Environmental Protection Agency)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

This is a request under the Freedom of Information Act. I hereby request the following records:

1. A list of any and all political appointments at the agency appointed from January 20, 2025 until the date of your final response to this request.

2. Copies of resumes for any and all political appointees hired since January 20, 2025 until the date of your final response to this request. These records are likely in the possession of the Designated Agency Ethics Official (DAEO).

Please provide these records as available on a rolling basis.

Documented is an investigative watchdog and reporting group that explores the relationship between special interests and government. This request is likely to contribute significantly to the public’s understanding of the operations of the government. Disclosure of the requested records serves the public interest, and this request is not being made for any commercial purposes. Therefore, I am requesting a waiver of any fees. If you do not grant my fee waiver request, please notify me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request be filled electronically by email attachment or other electronic file transfer if available, or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter.  I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,
Nina

Sincerely,

David Cavise

title: Keystone Pipeline Permit Decisions, Environmental Assessments, and Internal Communications (2017-2021)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Keystone Pipeline Permit Decisions, Environmental Assessments, and Internal Communications (2017-2021)
communications.communication:
Date:  January 12th ,2024
Via Email and Certified Mail:

Headquarters, U.S. Army Corps of Engineers
441 G Street NW
Washington, DC 20314-1000


Subject: FOIA Request - Keystone Pipeline Permit Decisions, Environmental Assessments, and Internal Communications (2017-2021)

Dear U.S. Army Corps of Engineers,

I am submitting this request under the Freedom of Information Act (5 U.S. Code § 552) for access to and copies of records from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers pertaining to the Keystone Pipeline permit. This request specifically targets decision-making processes, environmental assessments, policy implications, internal communications, and interactions with TC Energy or its affiliates during President Donald Trump's administration (January 20, 2017, to January 20, 2021).

Specific Areas of Inquiry:

Permit Processing and Decision Making (2017-2021):

Documentation detailing the processing, review, and decisions regarding the Keystone Pipeline permit.
Communications involving Corps officials and senior administration figures, particularly focusing on the involvement of Secretary of Energy Dan Brouillette.
Environmental Assessments and Impact Reports (2017-2021):

Environmental impact studies and assessments conducted or reviewed by the Corps regarding the Keystone Pipeline.
Internal discussions, memos, or reports addressing environmental concerns or risks.
Internal Communications (2017-2021):

Internal emails, memos, and communications within the Corps regarding the Keystone Pipeline project.
Discussions and correspondence that provide insight into the internal perspectives and debates about the project.
Communications with TC Energy and Affiliates (2017-2021):

Records of communications between the Corps and TC Energy or its affiliates.
Documentation of any meetings or negotiations involving TC Energy representatives.
External Influence and Lobbying (2017-2021):

Records detailing lobbying efforts or attempts to influence the Corps regarding the Keystone Pipeline permit.
Evidence of external entities' influence on the Corps' decision-making processes.
Legal Citations and Compliance:

Department of Justice v. Tax Analysts, 492 U.S. 136, 142 (1989)
Environmental Protection Agency v. Mink, 410 U.S. 73 (1973)
Favish v. National Archives and Records Administration, 541 U.S. 157 (2004)
American Civil Liberties Union v. Department of Justice, 655 F.3d 1 (D.C. Cir. 2011)
Fees and Waiver Request:
Enclosed is a Fee Waiver Request Form, requesting a waiver of all fees as this information is intended for public dissemination, per 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(4)(A)(iii).

Response Timeframe and Legal Implications:
A response is expected within the statutory 20-day period as mandated by FOIA. Non-compliance or undue delay may result in legal action to enforce FOIA compliance.

Record Keeping for Legal Purposes:
Please assign a unique identifier to this FOIA request and reference it in all related correspondence.

Your prompt and thorough attention to this request is greatly appreciated. I look forward to your comprehensive response.

Sincerely,

Jordan Lassiter

Enclosure: Fee Waiver Request Form

communications.communication:
Mr. Lassiter,


  This will acknowledge receipt of your FOIA request dated January 16, 2024 by the US Army Corps of Engineers, Omaha District (Agency).  The agency tracking number is FA-24-0037.  Under the FOIA, your request is in the “educational/news media” fee category. This category grants the requester the first 100 duplicated pages, along with search and review time, free of charge. Thereafter you would be responsible for duplication costs associated with the processing of your request (duplication costs include time spent converting electronic files to non-editable format). However, the fee waiver that you filed has been accepted and as such you will not be charged any fees for the processing of your request.



  Due to the current coronavirus pandemic, the Omaha District is experiencing delays in our ability to process FOIA requests. Because our office currently has a backlog of requests, your request will be placed on a calendar/tracking system behind others received before it, and each is processed in the order it was received. Should you have any questions please feel free to contact me.



Thank you,
Nicole Day

title: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order

communications.subject: Washington Public Records Act Request: Flock Safety search audits, network sharing, and general order
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the department’s Flock Safety system:
1. Organization Audit in Flock. 
The report should include data logged from the period of June 1, 2025, to June 30, 2025. Per Flock's documentation, the Organization Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches done within the agency.

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of June 1, 2025, to June 30, 2025. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.

3. A list of network share settings that include:
3a. Flock networks shared with me
3b. Networks that I’m sharing

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

communications.subject: Your City of Prosser, WA public records request #25-206 has been closed.
communications.communication:
City of Prosser, WA ************************************************************************ Record request #25-206 has been closed. The closure reason supplied was: Pursuant to RCW 42.56.520, the City of Prosser has received your request. The documents the City believes are responsive to your request are attached. Please be aware that the City searched its records only. The databank we searched does not account for any other agency, community, or police department. This response completes your request. If our interpretation of your request is incorrect, please notify me in writing by clarifying the intent of your request.  After review, it was determined that the request for Flock’s Network Audit records does not meet the definition of a “public record” under the Washington Public Records Act, RCW 42.56.010(3). A public record includes any writing prepared, owned, used, or retained by a state or local government agency that contains information relating to the conduct of government or the performance of any governmental or proprietary function. Specifically, the records requested are not prepared, owned, used, or retained by the City in a manner that constitutes a public record under the PRA. The requested documents consist of Flock’s reporting of which other agencies accessed data; the City does not prepare, own, use, or retain this audit report. Therefore, the portion of the request for Flock’s network audits is denied because the document does not meet the definition of a public record under RCW 42.56.010(3). Thank you, City of Prosser Staff www.cityofprosser.com City Hall (509) 786-2332 Police Business Office (509)786-1500 ************************************************************************ Questions about your request? Reply to this email or sign in to contact staff at City of Prosser, WA.

title: Evergreen Solutions (Prince George's Community College)

communications.subject: Maryland Public Information Act Request: Evergreen Solutions (Prince George's Community College)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Maryland Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

To Whom It May Concern:


Subject: Request for Public Records - 

Greetings,

I hope this email finds you well. We at Evergreen Solutions, LLC, are conducting a compensation study on behalf of our client and I am writing to make a formal open records request. We are requesting an electronic copy of your staff and faculty (if applicable) database as well as relevant documents such as job descriptions, collective bargaining agreements, and pay plans. I am able to send survey templates to assist with the data collection; however, we will accept data in the manner most convenient for you.

Staff Census Information requested:

Job Titles
Classification Title
Pay Grades
Pay Ranges (Minimum and Maximum)
Actual Salaries
Full-Time Equivalent (FTE) Status
Staff Handbook

I also kindly request answers to the following questions related to the compensation study:

How are salaries adjusted for your organization (e.g., COLA, Longevity, performance, etc.)?
What is your current turnover rate?
What is your current average tenure for an employee?
Date your current compensation plan was implemented.
Date of the last salary adjustment?
How frequently are job descriptions updated?

For the faculty database, I am requesting the following information:

Faculty Census:
Rank (if applicable)
Classification Title (if faculty holds other positions other than teaching such as Dean, Chair, Coordinators,etc)
Highest Degree Held
Pay Grade
Pay Ranges (Min& Max)
Current Step (if on a step plan)
Contract Length (in days and/or months)
Annual Base Salary with no additives
Annual Salary with any additives
Discipline (Not to be confused with department, the distinct/specific subject the faculty member teaches; Ex: Microbiology)
Department
CIP Code (if available - by individual incumbent)

Additionally, copies of the following documents, if available:

Copy of all faculty pay plans
Employee Benefit Information (Holidays Off, Health Insurance, Etc)
Salary Adjustment Policy (Longevity, performance, COLA, etc)
Any Collective Bargaining Agreements
Current Turnover Rate
Current Average Tenure
Date that your current pay plan was implemented
Date of your last salary adjustment to pay plan
How frequently are your job descriptions updated
Do you have a planned salary adjustment to your compensation structures for the next fiscal year? If so, by what amount?
Please list/attach and supplements/additives that faculty are compensated for duties outside of instruction
Faculty Handbooks
Adjunct Rates/Pay Plan
Overload Rates
Rates for compensation for faculty leadership- Deans, Coordinators, Department Chairs
Do you compensate faculty differently based on area of discipline? If yes, please provide details.
Do you have any form of additional compensation for Large Class Size? If yes, please provide details.
Do you have an education incentive at your institution? If yes, please provide details.

I understand that public records requests may involve administrative processes and associated fees, as allowed by law. Please inform me of any fees and the estimated timeframe for fulfilling this request. If any portion of this request is denied, please provide a written explanation for the denial, citing the specific legal grounds for the refusal.

Please consider this email as a formal request for public records under the applicable open records laws. If there are any questions or additional details needed to process this request, please do not hesitate to contact me.

I look forward to your prompt attention to this matter and the timely provision of the requested information. Your cooperation in ensuring transparency and access to public records is greatly appreciated.

Do you agree to the redaction of information that is subject to mandatory exceptions, provided such redactions are clearly labeled on information you receive?: Yes
Do you agree to the redaction of information that is subject to discretionary exceptions, provided such redactions are clearly labeled on information you receive? Yes

Email: alisia@consultevergreen.com

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Alisia Rios

Good Afternoon,

This email is once again intended for Alisia Rios, Data Analyst at Evergreen Solutions, LLC.

Ms. Rios, on March 19, 2025, I notified you that Prince George's Community College (the College) had received your extensive MPIA request upon return from its spring break on March 17, 2025. I advised that I had asked the departments who may have access to responsive documents for an estimated time for their efforts, and noted that the College charges fees for all time expended beyond the first two hours.  PGCC's MPIA fee schedule (and other FAQs about PGCC's MPIA processing) can be found at this link: https://www.pgcc.edu/about-pgcc/institutional-information--policies/maryland-public-information-act-mpia-requests/.

In this case, the College estimates that it will take 2 employees 8 hours each to fulfill the request, with one employee researching the faculty and staff census information, and the other gathering documents listed at the bottom of the request. Based on salary, one employee's hourly compensation is $57.27, and the other's hourly compensation is $61.25. Thus, PGCC estimates that you would be charged $711.12 for the production of records to fulfill your request ($57.27 x 6 additional hours PLUS $61.25 x 6 additional hours). Because the information would be provided electronically, you would not be charged any additional fees for the production of records in a type of medium (CD, photographs, etc.). Please note that this is an estimate, and the actual fee for the collection of records pursuant to this request may be fewer or greater than $711.12

Under the MPIA, you may seek a fee waiver if 1) you are indigent or 2) you believe a waiver would be in the public interest.

Please confirm whether you still wish to receive the information. If so, we will gather the information and provide you with the actual fee amount, and connect you with the Bursar's office for collection of payment prior to releasing the information.

Greetings,
I hope this message finds you well.

We are currently in the process of submitting the document as discussed. Before proceeding with payment, my project manager has asked that we confirm the contents of the information we will be receiving. In the past, we've had experiences with other organizations where, unfortunately, we completed payment but did not receive all of the requested data.

To avoid any confusion or delays, would it be possible for you to provide a brief summary of the materials being sent? This will help us ensure everything is accounted for prior to payment.

For reference, here is an example of the type of summary we’re looking for:

1. Staff Census
(Includes job classification, FTE status, pay ranges, and salary grades)

2. Staff Handbook
(Employee policies, code of conduct, benefits, and general procedures)

3. Staff Policies
(Attendance, leave, performance evaluations, remote work, etc.)

4. Job Descriptions
(For all staff-classified employees, including roles, responsibilities, and qualifications)

Thank you in advance for your understanding and assistance. We look forward to receiving the summary so we can move forward accordingly.

title: E & A Occupancy + Fire Sprinkler Information (Public Works Department)

communications.subject: Texas Public Information Act Request: E & A Occupancy + Fire Sprinkler Information (Public Works Department)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I respectfully request an electronic, parcel-level extract containing current Group E (Educational) and Group A (Assembly) occupancies and associated fire-sprinkler information for all parcels within the jurisdiction: 

Please provide one CSV with the following columns (your native field names are fine):
- Parcel identifier (APN / PIN / BBL)
• Site address (street #, street, city, ZIP)
• Latitude & longitude
• Internal building / permit ID
• Year built
• Floor area (sq ft)
• Number of stories
• Current IBC occupancy code (E, A-1…A-5)
• Occupancy description
• Fire-sprinkler present (Yes / No / Unknown)
• Date of last fire-sprinkler inspection (if tracked)
• Owner name & mailing address (if stored)

If any field is not maintained, please note that rather than withholding the entire record.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

David Cavise

title: Social media guidance 10/07 onward (Department of Defense, Freedom of Information Policy Office)

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Social media guidance 10/07 onward (Department of Defense, Freedom of Information Policy Office)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

1) From October 7, 2023 to the time that this request is processed: A copy of any official guidance provided to, or created by, the head of social media or communications for this department — specifically, guidance regarding public communications or posts about the Israel/Gaza conflict.

Note 1: These documents may be referred to as guidance documents, social media policy documents, memoranda, letters, notes from meetings, or emails.

Note 2: If you need a keyword search, please search for the following terms:
—“Israel"
—“Gaza"
—“Hamas
—“Palestine"
—“Palestinian"
—"Students for Justice in Palestine"
—“SJP"
—“Chabad
—"Hillel”

Note 3: Please limit the scope of this request to the head of communications/social media for this department.

This FOI request is being filed in pursuit of a time-sensitive news story. Therefore, I ask that my request is expedited. When completing this request, please prioritize whichever records would take the least amount of time to be located and released. I would like these records in electronic format, sent via email or other digital method, and again, please release documents on a rolling basis, as they become available.

If you determine that any of the information qualifies for an exemption from disclosure, I ask you to note whether the exemption is discretionary, and if so whether it is necessary in this case to exercise your discretion to withhold the information. In any event, please provide a signed notification citing the legal authorities on which you rely if you determine that any of the information is exempt and will not be disclosed.

Also, I am a member of the news media as a reporter for Business Insider, and the requested documents are in the public interest and not being made for commercial purposes. Therefore, I ask that all fees are waived in the processing of my request. If fees associated with this request will be in excess of $25, kindly notify me in advance of fulfilling this request. As I am making this request as a journalist and this information is timely, I would appreciate your communicating with me if you have questions regarding this request.

Thanks again, and if there are any questions about my request, can provide any clarification that will help expedite the processing of my request, please contact me at email address. I am also happy to hop on the phone.

I look forward to your reply within 20 business days, as the statute requires and an even more prompt reply if you can make a determination without having to review the records in question.

Thank you for your time and attention to this matter.

Best,
Caroline

title: FOIA Request on Christopher Hitchens

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: FOIA Request on Christopher Hitchens
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any files the FBI has access to that pertain to the British writer and intellectual Christopher Hitchens (1949-2011). The bulk of the files will likely be from 1992 through 2008. 

In order to help determine my status to assess fees, you should know that I am requesting the file in my capacity as a Research Assistant to Stephen Phillips, a writer and reporter currently working on a biography of Christopher Hitchens at the CUNY Graduate Center's Leon Levy Center.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Maks Bondarenko

communications.subject: Re: Production Status of SB 1421 Files
communications.communication:
Dear SB1421 Requesters and interested parties,

It has come to my attention that the City of Fullerton has broken California’s Public Record’s Law, specifically related to SB1421, by denying you records which are quite clearly publicly disclosable.

In the link sent to you by Mea Klein, Assistant City Clerk, as provided to her by the City Attorney, you were told that there are 27 Officers "REQUESTED BY NAME, BUT NO DISCLOSABLE FILE AVAILABLE (27)”. This is patently false.

The City of Fullerton is currently suing me, my compatriot David and the blog Friends for Fullerton’s Future directly related to the findings on several of these officers.

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/city-of-fullerton-is-suing-me-and-this-blog/ <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/city-of-fullerton-is-suing-me-and-this-blog/>

In looking at this list I can quite easily name Officers on that list who have disclosable records under SB1421 including but not limited to Kathryn Hamel, Paul Irish, Miguel “Sonny” Siliceo, Christopher Wren & Nathan Roesler.

A sustained finding was found against Hamel and one cannot simply unring that bell as seen in the recent Contra Costa County tentative decision (CASE NAME: RICHMOND POLICE VS. CITY OF RICHMOND <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/wp-content/uploads/2020/09/Contra-Costa-Ruling-Case-MSN19-0169-2020-07-31.pdf>). 

This FFFF article related to Hamel is specifically mentioned in the lawsuit against myself and FFFF:

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/fullerton-police-cut-a-deal-to-bypass-the-law/ <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/fullerton-police-cut-a-deal-to-bypass-the-law/>

Christopher Wren had a sustained finding against for dishonesty related to a workplace affair with a subordinate. In IA Case #17-0038 one of the sustained findings against Officer Wren is as follows:

“6. On December 17, 2017, when Lieutenant Cleggett asked you about your whereabouts, you dishonestly stated to Lieutenant Cleggett that you had been on the phone with your wife the entire time and did not notice Lieutenant Cleggett’s text message.”

This statement of dishonesty was directly related to misconduct as outlined in the timeline of Wren’s activities and being in violation of policy. 

Likewise with Christopher Wren, this article is specifically listed in the lawsuit being waged against myself and FFFF:

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/what-happened-to-officer-christopher-wren/

The idea that the city attorney is unaware of the sustained findings against their officers which are disclosable under SB1421 is laughable when those very stories are being used by the same attorneys as evidence in a lawsuit where the city seeks a prior restraint against myself and FFFF.

The blog has likewise published stories on how Paul Irish was terminated for dishonesty;

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/fullertons-veritable-serpico-problem/ <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2019/fullertons-veritable-serpico-problem/>

Miguel “Sonny” Siliceo admitted in the plea deal that he both used excessive force and falsified a police report.

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2018/sonnys-admission-guilt/ <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2018/sonnys-admission-guilt/>

Nathan Roesler filed a false report with the City of Placentia which resulted in an innocent man being arrested for a crime that wasn’t committed against Roesler. This was referred to the District Attorney for prosecution.

https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2018/another-possible-cover-up-by-fpd/ <https://www.fullertonsfuture.org/2018/another-possible-cover-up-by-fpd/>

These are the cases which are readily and easily pointed out which I believe to be disclosable under SB1421 which calls all of the other officers on the list into question. The City is blatantly lying to you, your organizations and agencies as well as the public and concerned entities about disclosable records despite being in a separate lawsuit over these very violations of SB1421.

They are likewise violating the law in regards to the officer whose records are "PENDING; NOT YET PRODUCED (3)”. The incident in Corbett’s case was from 2016 and Paez’s was in 2017. The timeline has long passed for required production in both of these cases.

If you are honestly seeking these records and others from the City of Fullerton you will likely have no recourse but to seek remedies in order to get to the truth. I have already been forced to take this route unfortunately.

Thank you for your time and I wish you all the best in your efforts.

Sincerely,

Joshua Ferguson
Host, The Hourly Struggle
Writer, Friends for Fullerton’s Future
Concerned Citizen

communications.subject: Fullerton Production Status of SB 1421 Files
communications.communication:
Dear SB 1421 requesters and interested parties:
You have each recently received a mass email communication from an individual with whom the City of Fullerton is currently engaged in civil litigation, Joshua Ferguson.  The email contained inaccuracies about the City's responses to Public Records requests.  The City would like to correct certain information and assure you and other members of the public of its commitment to transparency and compliance with legal requirements for the disclosure of public records, including certain peace officer records recently made public under SB 1421, which is codified at Penal Code section 832.7.  Of course, the City cannot respond as to any specifics about any individual officers referenced, due to privacy.

Disclosable use of force files:
Not all use of force investigation files are disclosable under SB 1421.  SB 1421 only allows the disclosure of those files involving uses of force that have resulted in death or "great bodily injury."  Pen. Code section 832.7(b)(1)(A)(ii).  "Great bodily injury" means "significant or substantial physical injury."  Pen. Code section 16600.  Examples of "great bodily injury" include: broken bones, People v. Villarreal (1985) 173 Cal.App.3d 1136, 1141; gunshot wounds, People v. Mendias (1993) 17 Cal.App.4th 195; and a dog bite, People v. Frazier (2009) 173 Cal. App. 4th 613, 618.  SB 1421 also mandates the disclosure of investigation files involving a peace officer or custodial officer's discharge of a firearm at a civilian.  See Pen. Code section 832.7(b)(1)(A)(i).

Disclosable dishonesty files:
Not all dishonesty investigation files are disclosable under SB 1421.  SB 1421 only allows the disclosure of "sustained finding[s] . . . [of] dishonesty by a peace officer or custodial officer directly relating to the reporting, investigation, or prosecution of a crime, or directly relating to the reporting of, or investigation of misconduct by, another peace officer or custodial officer, including but not limited to, any sustained finding of perjury, false statements, filing false reports, destruction, falsifying, or concealing of evidence."  See Cal. Penal Code section 832.7(b)(1)(C) (emphasis added).
The Legislature intended to provide the public access to cases involving dishonesty, where an officer "is proven to have planted evidence, committed perjury, or otherwise been dishonest in the reporting, investigation, or prosecution of a crime."  Assembly Committee on Public Safety, Analysis of SB 1421 (June 26, 2018).

In order for acts of dishonesty to be disclosable under SB 1421, there must also have been a "sustained" finding of dishonesty.  A "sustained finding" is defined as "a final determination by an investigating agency, commission, board, hearing officer, or arbitrator, as applicable, following an investigation and opportunity for an administrative appeal pursuant to Sections 3304 and 3304.5 of the Government Code, that the actions of the peace officer or custodial officer were found to violate law or department policy."  Pen. Code section 832.8 (emphasis added).

If an officer investigated for the type dishonesty or sexual assault that is disclosable under SB 1421 resigns prior to a sustained finding, his or her file is not disclosable.

Although the email that you received referred to a specific court ruling (Richmond Police Officers' Ass'n v. City of Richmond), that ruling was only tentative (not final) and was only the ruling of one Superior Court Judge in Contra Costa County.  The City of Fullerton is located in Orange County, and is not subject to those courts or their rulings.  However, even a ruling in Orange County would not have been determinative, as facts in different cases may lead to different results, and a single judge's opinion is not required to be followed by other judges, until there is some binding opinion of higher courts.  In fact, in City of Richmond, that court found that the employer and an officer could not reverse sustained findings of dishonesty or sexual assault through a negotiated settlement, after the conclusion of a formal hearing process.  In circumstances where a final, formal hearing has not been held, the court acknowledged that there would be no "sustained findings" and hence such records are "not disclosable under SB 1421."  (The City of Richmond court also noted that investigations of dishonesty involving subjects not specifically listed in Penal Code section 832.7 are also not disclosable).

Regardless of the inapplicability of the City of Richmond opinion in Orange County, the City of Fullerton's disclosure of its records under SB 1421 does follow the same principles.

The City is committed to providing all records that it is required and permitted to release to the public relating to peace officers.  It has been working hard to review and release all records newly made releasable since the enactment of SB 1421, and will continue to do so. The City has produced 26 SB 1421 files; has partially produced 13 additional SB 1421 files; and has 2 SB 1421 files pending review (one of which awaits resolution of administrative or other proceedings).  The City's SB 1421 productions are available at www.cityoffullerton.com/sb1421<http://www.cityoffullerton.com/sb1421>, and a copy of the summary chart detailing the progress of the City's SB 1421 review and production is posted therein.

If you have any questions or concerns about your requests or the City's production thereto, please contact the City Clerk's Office or the City Attorney's Office.

Kimberly Hall Barlow
Jones & Mayer
3777 N. Harbor Boulevard
Fullerton, California 92835
714-446-1400 Telephone
714-446-1448 Facsimile
khb@jones-mayer.com<mailto:khb@jones-mayer.com>

title: Request for Information on MQ-9A Reaper Flight from Kanoya Air Base, Japan on February 3rd, 2023

communications.subject: Freedom of Information Act Request: Request for Information on MQ-9A Reaper Flight from Kanoya Air Base, Japan on February 3rd, 2023
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Freedom of Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

Any and all information regarding equipment attached to any MQ-9A Reaper flights on February 3rd, 2023 from Kanoya Air Base in Japan.
Any and all information regarding sensor capabilities in use during any MQ-9A Reaper flights on February 3rd, 2023 from Kanoya Air Base in Japan.
Any and all information regarding any MQ-9A Reaper flights on February 3rd, 2023 from Kanoya Air Base in Japan, including but not limited to video recordings, flight paths, aircraft serial numbers, chat logs, and mission reports.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 20 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Amelia Smith

title: Public Records Request – Interrogation & Investigation Records: Michael Crowe (Stephanie Crowe Murder; Jan 1998)

communications.subject: California Public Records Act Request: Public Records Request – Interrogation & Investigation Records: Michael Crowe (Stephanie Crowe Murder; Jan 1998)
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the California Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

I respectfully request access to public records relating to the criminal investigation and interrogation of Michael Crowe, age 14, in connection with the murder of his sister, Stephanie Crowe, in January 1998, in Escondido, CA.

Requested Records:

1. Complete video and/or audio recordings of all interrogations of Michael Crowe, including multiple sessions conducted between January 21–23, 1998.


2. Transcripts or written summaries of those interrogations, if available.


3. Interrogation and investigation memos, police reports, indices or logs summarizing the interviews and collection of evidence.


4. Any internal reviews, assessments, or complaints regarding interrogation methods used in connection with the Crowe case.


5. Correspondence relating to media or external inquiries, including any communication with Court TV, Oprah, or other journalists regarding the case.

 Identifying Details:

Incident: Murder of Stephanie Crowe; Michael became the focus of multiple extended interrogations.

Approx. Dates: January 21 through January 23, 1998.

Jurisdiction: Escondido Police Department, San Diego County.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 calendar days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Brown Pearl

title: Cleveland Police Department: Social media settings

communications.subject: Ohio Open Records Law Request: Cleveland Police Department: Social media settings
communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Ohio Open Records Law, I hereby request the following records:

This request seeks records relating to the Facebook page located at https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept. An example of what each of these records look like is attached and available at https://bit.ly/facebookfoia.

In order to access the requested information, you will first need to take the following steps:

1. Log into the page account or a Facebook account with managerial access to the Facebook page. For information on this type of access, see: https://www.facebook.com/help/187316341316631.)
2. "Switch" to the page account. To do so, click your profile photo in the top right, then click "See all profiles", then select the Page you want to switch into. (See the instructions here: https://www.facebook.com/help/123930246348340).
3. Click "Professional dashboard" on the left, or go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept/?sk=professional_dashboard

I request the following information:

1. The "Page and Tagging" information. Once logged into the account, go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings/?tab=timeline&privacy_source=timeline_gear_menu. 

2. The list of blocked users. This information is accessible by following these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings?tab=blocking
(b) Click "Edit" next to "Block users" 
(c) Click "See your blocked list"

3. The list of blocked Pages. This information is accessible by following these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings?tab=blocking
(b) Click "Edit" next to "Block Pages" 
(c) Click "See your blocked list"

4. The list of "Moderation Assist" criteria. This information is accessible by following either of these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to the "Professional Dashboard" and then click "Moderation Assist" on the left side of the screen.
(b) Alternatively, visit this URL: https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept/professional_dashboard/moderation_assist

5. If the "Moderation Assist" criteria includes "Comment has certain keywords", the list of keywords. This information is accessible by following the steps in (4) above, then:
(a) Click the pencil (edit) icon next to each of the criteria ("Comment has certain keywords").
(b) Click "Edit" from the drop-down menu.
(c) Click "Comment has certain keywords"
(d) On the right side of the "Keywords" menu, click the ellipsis menu ("...")
(e) Click "Copy list" from the dropdown menu.
(f) Provide the information from the list.

6. If the "Moderation Assist" criteria includes "Comment has specific links", the list of keywords. This information is accessible by following the steps in (4) above, then:
(a) Click the pencil (edit) icon next to each of the criteria ("Comment has specific links").
(b) Click "Edit" from the drop-down menu.
(c) Click "Comment has links to specific sites."
(d) Provide the information from the "Added sites" list.

7. The list of people with Facebook access. From the "Professional dashboard" page (https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept/?sk=professional_dashboard), click "Page Access" on the left side of the screen. Alternatively, visit this URL: https://www.facebook.com/settings/?tab=profile_access

8. The list of moderation actions in the Activity log. This information is accessible by following these steps:
(a) Once logged into the account, go to the "Professional Dashboard."
(b) Click "Moderation Assist" on the left side of the screen (or go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept/professional_dashboard/moderation_assist).
(c) Click "Activity log" on the left side of the screen (or go to this URL: https://www.facebook.com/ClevelandPoliceDept/professional_dashboard/moderation_activity_log).
(c) From the dropdown menu labeled "Visible comments", select "Hidden comments".
(d) Continue scrolling down until the complete list is loaded.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 10 business days.

Sincerely,

Adam Steinbaugh

The District of Columbia is required to respond to your FOIA request within fifteen (15) business days of its receipt.  See D.C. Official Code § 2-532(c)(2011).  However, under certain circumstances, D.C. Official Code § 2-532(d)(2011) authorizes the District to extend, by ten (10) additional days, the deadline by which it must respond to a FOIA request.  One of the circumstances provided by that statute is a case in which the District needs additional time to search for, collect and examine voluminous amounts of records and/or consult with an additional D.C. agency. 
For any questions regarding your request, please contact the FOIA office directly. Find the list of agency Open Government and FOIA contact information by visiting FOIA Contact Information. For ease of reference, we ask that you have your FOIA Reference Number available when you contact the FOIA office. 
Regards, 
District of Columbia

communications.subject: [Records Center] Public Records Request :: R012258-070125
communications.communication:
Dear Elijah Pittman, 
 
 
RE: PUBLIC RECORDS REQUEST of July 01, 2025, Reference # R012258-070125 
 
 
 
I send this note with regard to the Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request that you submitted to the DPW - Department of Public Works and assigned as Request Number R012258-070125 received on 7/1/2025. 
As you may know, DPW - Department of Public Works is required to respond to your FOIA request within fifteen (15) business days of its receipt.  See D.C. Official Code § 2-532(c)(2011).  However, under certain circumstances, D.C. Official Code § 2-532(d)(2011) authorizes the District to extend, by ten (10) additional days, the deadline by which it must respond to a FOIA request.  One of the circumstances provided by that statute is a case in which the District needs additional time to search for, collect and examine voluminous amounts of records and/or consult with an additional D.C. agency.  Pursuant to the above-referenced statute, the District has extended, by ten (10) days, the deadline by which it must respond to your FOIA request. We anticipate responding to your FOIA request on, or before 8/6/2025. 
Please know that, under D.C. Official Code § 2-537 and 1 DCMR 412, you have the right to appeal this response to the Mayor or to the Superior Court of the District of Columbia. If you elect to appeal to the Mayor, your appeal must be in writing and contain “Freedom of Information Act Appeal” or “FOIA Appeal” in the subject line of the letter as well on the outside of the envelope. The appeal must include (1) a copy of the original request; (2) a copy of any written denial; (3) a statement of the circumstances, reasons, and/or arguments advanced in support of disclosure; and (4) a daytime telephone number, and e-mail and/or U.S. Mail address at which you can be reached. The appeal must be mailed to: The Mayor’s Correspondence Unit, FOIA Appeal; 1350 Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W., Suite 316, Washington, D.C. 20004. Electronic versions of the same information can instead be e-mailed to The Mayor’s Correspondence Unit at foia.mayor@dc.gov 
 
 The following only applies to the Office of the Attorney General OAG: 
 Please note that under DC Code § 2-537(a-2), “[a]ny person denied the right to inspect a public record in the possession of the Attorney General may institute proceedings in the Superior Court of the District of Columbia for injunctive or declaratory relief, or for an order to enjoin the public body from withholding the record and to compel the production of the requested record.” 
Thank you. 
Jacqueline Williams 
Department of Public Works

communications.subject: [Records Center] Public Records Request :: R012258-070125
communications.communication:
--- Please respond above this line --- 
Dear Elijah Pittman, Thank you for speaking with me today. You clarified your request indicating that you are in possession of photos of the vehicle that is the subject of your request-- a DC Department of Transportation vehicle. This letter acknowledges and responds to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request #R012258-070125 to the DC Department of Public Works (DPW). You requested the following records: “Information including but not limited to documents like registration reports, procurement agreements, contracts, about D.C. government owned and operated Rivian vehicle with number "98 16037" and Washington, D.C. license plate number "DC 16037" used for. I also request documents pertaining to the purchasing and maintenance of Rivian vehicles and any documents containing the number of total Rivian vehicles in the D.C. fleet.” DPW provides municipal services in two distinct program areas: solid waste management and parking enforcement. Both contribute to making District streets and public spaces clean, safe, attractive, and accessible. DPW's Solid Waste Management Administration performs a number of daily operations including trash and recycling collection, sanitation education and enforcement, graffiti removal, public litter can service, fall leaf collection, and street and alley cleaning. DPW's Parking Enforcement Management Administration enforces the District's on-street parking laws. Approximately 200 parking officers monitor 17,000 meters and 3,500 blocks of residential zoned parking. In addition to routine enforcement, the Parking Enforcement Management Administration is charged with booting and towing operations and with removing abandoned and dangerous vehicles from public and private property. Behind the scenes, DPW's Fleet Management Administration supports municipal operations by procuring, fueling, and maintaining thousands of District government vehicles, from sedans to heavy equipment. Some vehicles are managed and maintained independently by certain agencies. Fleet Management also is responsible for purchasing environmentally friendly, alternative-fuel vehicles (AFV) for the city. Please be advised that DPW maintains information partially responsive to your request. Specifically, DPW is aware of fifty-six (56) Rivian vehicles within the District’s fleet. However, the District of Columbia Department of Transportation manages and maintains all the vehicles. Your FOIA requests concerning procurement agreements and contracts should be submitted to the DC Office of Procurement, FOIA Officer Jeremiah Regan, 441 4th Street NW, Washington, DC 20001, email: jeremiah.regan@dc.gov , phone: (202) 727-0252. Your FOIA requests related to vehicle registrations should be sent to DC Department of Motor Vehicles Pamela Washington, Assistant General Counsel, District of Columbia Department of Motor Vehicles, 95 M Street, SW, Washington, DC 20024-3622, phone (202) 729-7113; email: pamela.washington@dc.gov. (mailto:pamela.washington@dc.gov) Your requests related to maintenance should be sent to Nana Bailey-Thomas, Esq., Hearings/FOIA Officer, Office of the General Counsel, at the District Department of Transportation, 250 M Street, S.E., Suite 800, Washington, D.C. 20003; phone: (202) 673-6811; Email: nana.bailey@dc.gov. (mailto:nana.bailey@dc.gov) Therefore, FOIA request #R012258-070125 is . GRANTED IN PART Please note, under D.C. Official Code § 2-537 and 1 DCMR 412, you have the right to appeal this response to the Mayor or to the Superior Court of the District of Columbia. If you elect to appeal to the Mayor, your appeal must be in writing and contain “Freedom of Information Act Appeal” or “FOIA Appeal” in the subject line of the letter as well on the outside of the envelope. The appeal must include (1) a copy of the original request; (2) a copy of any written denial; (3) a statement of the circumstances, reasons, and/or arguments advanced in support of disclosure; and (4) a daytime telephone number, and e-mail and/or U.S. Mail address at which you can be reached. The appeal must be mailed to: The Mayor’s Correspondence Unit, FOIA Appeal; 1350 Pennsylvania Avenue, N.W., Suite 316, Washington, D.C. 20004. Electronic versions of the same information can instead be e-mailed to The Mayor’s Correspondence Unit at foia.mayor@dc.gov Further, you must forward a copy of all appeal materials to the Freedom of Information Officer of the involved agency or to the agency head if there is no designated Freedom of Information Officer.  Failure to follow these administrative steps will delay the processing and commencement of a response to your appeal. Sincerely, /s/ Jacqueline Williams Assistant General Counsel Department of Public Works

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Washington Public Records Act, I hereby request the following records:

Records related to the department’s Flock Safety system:
1. Organization Audit in Flock. 
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Organization Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches done within the agency.

2. Network Audit in Flock.
The report should include data logged from the period of December 1, 2024, to the date this request is processed. Per Flock's documentation, the Network Audit is available within the Insights tab and is defined as searches of the organization’s Flock network by any agency in the Flock System.

3. A list of network share settings that include:
3a. Flock networks shared with me
3b. Networks that I’m sharing

Please provide records in their original electronic, machine readable format. For example, please provide csv or spreadsheet files where applicable. Please do not redirect me to your transparency portal.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

In the event that there are fees, I would be grateful if you would inform me of the total charges in advance of fulfilling my request. I would prefer the request filled electronically, by e-mail attachment if available or CD-ROM if not.

Thank you in advance for your anticipated cooperation in this matter. I look forward to receiving your response to this request within 5 business days, as the statute requires.

Sincerely,

Rose Terse

communications.communication:
To Whom It May Concern:

Pursuant to the Texas Public Information Act, I hereby request the following records:

I respectfully request an electronic, parcel-level extract containing current Group E (Educational) and Group A (Assembly) occupancies and associated fire-sprinkler information for all parcels within the jurisdiction: 

Please provide one CSV with the following columns (your native field names are fine):
- Parcel identifier (APN / PIN / BBL)
• Site address (street #, street, city, ZIP)
• Latitude & longitude
• Internal building / permit ID
• Year built
• Floor area (sq ft)
• Number of stories
• Current IBC occupancy code (E, A-1…A-5)
• Occupancy description
• Fire-sprinkler present (Yes / No / Unknown)
• Date of last fire-sprinkler inspection (if tracked)
• Owner name & mailing address (if stored)

If any field is not maintained, please note that rather than withholding the entire record.

The requested documents will be made available to the general public, and this request is not being made for commercial purposes.

05/16/2023Andrew FreeMuckRock News, DEPT MR145669Boston, Massachusetts 02115RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2023-ICFO-25563        Dear Requester:This acknowledges receipt of your 5/11/2023, Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), for all records pertaining to 2022-ICAP-01053 and 2021-ICFO-04070.  Your request was received in this office on 5/11/2023.Due to the increasing number of FOIA requests received by this office, we may encounter some delay in processing your request. Per Section 5.5(a) of the DHS FOIA regulations, 6 C.F.R. Part 5, ICE processes FOIA requests according to their order of receipt. Although ICE’s goal is to respond within 20 business days of receipt of your request, the FOIA does permit a 10-day extension of this time period. As your request seeks numerous documents that will necessitate a thorough and wide-ranging search, ICE will invoke a 10-day extension for your request, as allowed by Title 5 U.S.C. § 552(a)(6)(B). If you’re able to narrow the scope of your request please contact our office. Narrowing the scope may speed up the search process. We will make every effort to comply with your request in a timely manner.Provisions of the FOIA allow us to recover part of the cost of complying with your request.  We shall charge you for records in accordance with the DHS Interim FOIA regulations as they apply to non-commercial requesters.  As a non-commercial requester, you will be charged 10 cents per page for duplication; the first 100 pages are free, as are the first two hours of search time, after which you will pay the per quarter-hour rate ($4.00 for clerical personnel, $7.00 for professional personnel, $10.25 for managerial personnel) of the searcher.  We will construe the submission of your request as an agreement to pay up to $25.00. You will be contacted before any further fees are accrued.We have queried the appropriate program offices within ICE for responsive records. If any responsive records are located, they will be reviewed for determination of releasability. Please be assured that one of the processors in our office will respond to your request as expeditiously as possible. We appreciate your patience as we proceed with your request.If you have any questions, please contact FOIA Public Liaison, Fernando Pineiro Jr. at the address above or (866) 633-1182. Additionally, you have a right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448; or facsimile at 202-741-5769.Your request has been assigned reference number 2023-ICFO-25563. Please use this number in future correspondence. Sincerely,ICE FOIA OfficeImmigration and Customs EnforcementFreedom of Information Act Office500 12th Street, S.W., Stop 5009Washington, D.C. 20536-5009

communications.subject: ICE FOIA 2023-ICFO-25563
communications.communication:
Andrew Free 
MuckRock News, DEPT MR145669 
263 Huntington Ave 
Boston, Massachusetts 02115 

RE:	ICE FOIA Case Number 2023-ICFO-25563 

Dear Requester: 

This letter is the final response to your Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) request to U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement (ICE), dated 5/11/2023.  You have requested all records pertaining to 2022-ICAP-01053 and 2021-ICFO-04070. ICE has considered your request under the FOIA, 5 U.S.C. § 552. 

ICE considered the foreseeable harm standard when reviewing the record set and has applied the FOIA exemptions as required by the statute and the Attorney General’s Guidance. 

A search of the ICE Office of Enforcement and Removal Operations (ERO) for records responsive to your request produced 44 pages that are responsive to your request.  After review of those documents, I have determined portions of 44 pages will be withheld pursuant to Exemptions of the FOIA as described below. 

ICE has applied FOIA Exemptions 6 and 7(C) to protect from disclosure the names, e-mail addresses, and phone numbers of DHS employees, as well as other third-party information contained within the documents. 

FOIA Exemption 6 exempts from disclosure personnel or medical files and similar files the release of which would cause a clearly unwarranted invasion of personal privacy.  This requires a balancing of the public’s right to disclosure against the individual’s right to privacy.  The privacy interests of the individuals in the records you have requested outweigh any minimal public interest in disclosure of the information.  Any private interest you may have in that information does not factor into the aforementioned balancing test. 

FOIA Exemption 7(C) protects records or information compiled for law enforcement purposes that could reasonably be expected to constitute an unwarranted invasion of personal privacy.  This exemption takes particular note of the strong interests of individuals, whether they are suspects, witnesses, or investigators, in not being unwarrantably associated with alleged criminal activity.  That interest extends to persons who are not only the subjects of the investigation, but those who may have their privacy invaded by having their identities and information about them revealed in connection with an investigation.  Based upon the traditional recognition of strong privacy interest in law enforcement records, categorical withholding of information that identifies third parties in law enforcement records is ordinarily appropriate.  As such, I have determined that the privacy interest in the identities of individuals in the records you have requested clearly outweigh any minimal public interest in disclosure of the information.  Please note that any private interest you may have in that information does not factor into this determination. 

ICE has applied FOIA Exemption 7(E) to protect from disclosure internal agency case numbers and internal agency URLs contained within the document. 

FOIA Exemption 7(E) protects records compiled for law enforcement purposes, the release of which would disclose techniques and/or procedures for law enforcement investigations or prosecutions, or would disclose guidelines for law enforcement investigations or prosecutions if such disclosure could reasonably be expected to risk circumvention of the law.  I have determined that disclosure of certain law enforcement sensitive information contained within the responsive records could reasonably be expected to risk circumvention of the law.  Additionally, the techniques and procedures at issue are not well known to the public. 

You have a right to appeal the above withholding determination.  Should you wish to do so, you must send your appeal and a copy of this letter, within 90 days of the date of this letter following the procedures outlined in the DHS FOIA regulations at 6 C.F.R. Part 5 § 5.8. You may submit your appeal electronically at GILDFOIAAppeals@ice.dhs.gov or via regular mail to: 

U.S. Immigration and Customs Enforcement 
Office of the Principal Legal Advisor 
U.S. Department of Homeland Security 
500 12th Street, S.W., Mail Stop 5900 
Washington, D.C. 20536-5900 

Your envelope and letter should be marked “FOIA Appeal.”  Copies of the FOIA and DHS regulations are available at www.dhs.gov/foia. 

Provisions of FOIA allow DHS to charge for processing fees, up to $25, unless you seek a waiver of fees.  In this instance, because the cost is below the $25 minimum, there is no charge. 

If you have any questions please contact FOIA Public Liaison Daniel Edgington at (866) 633-1182 or 500 12th St., SW Stop 5009 Washington, DC 20536-5009.  Additionally, you have a right to right to seek dispute resolution services from the Office of Government Information Services (OGIS) which mediates disputes between FOIA requesters and Federal agencies as a non-exclusive alternative to litigation.  If you are requesting access to your own records (which is considered a Privacy Act request), you should know that OGIS does not have the authority to handle requests made under the Privacy Act of 1974.  You may contact OGIS as follows:  Office of Government Information Services, National Archives and Records Administration, 8601 Adelphi Road-OGIS, College Park, Maryland 20740-6001, e-mail at ogis@nara.gov; telephone at 202-741-5770; toll free at 1-877-684-6448. 

Sincerely, 

Megan Davis 
Deputy FOIA Officer, Operations 

Enclosure(s):	45 Pages 
Note: If you are receiving this message by email and responsive records are not included as an attachment to the email, please log in to your SecureRelease portal account to view the responsive records.
